<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12032j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12032j">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12032j"> 32(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> injurieuse verit&eacute;s</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">(La tragique aventure de l&apos;h&ocirc;telier de &ldquo; La Licorne&rdquo;]. Du Mont &agrave; la Bastille.): M. Mesl&eacute; ne prit pas les choses au tragique; le 26 juillet 1764, il &eacute;crivait &agrave; l&apos;intendant, &agrave; Caen: &ldquo;Deux femmes, au Mont-Saint-Michel, se sont prises de bec et, comme c&apos;est l&apos;ordinaire entre femelles de cette esp&egrave;ce, on s&apos;est dit et redit bien d&apos;injurieuses v&eacute;rit&eacute;s. Ridel, effray&eacute; de la pers&eacute;cution de ce gouverneur &agrave; longue robe noire, (le prieur) a enfil&eacute; la porte et s&apos;est r&eacute;fugi&eacute; &agrave; Avranches; je ris de l&apos;aventure et je <font color="green">[182]</font> vous la raconte en badinant; mais nos juges d&apos;Avranches le prennent sur un autre ton; l&apos;affaire sera s&eacute;rieuse, surtout pour Dom Hou&euml;l.&raquo;. <br><font color="green">[M. Mesl&eacute; was not a tragedian; on 26 July 1764, he wrote to the intendant at Caen: &ldquo; Two women, in Mont-Saint-Michel, began to fight and, as it is common with females of the species, they said and repeated quite a few injurious truths. Ridel, afraid of persecution by the governor of the long black robe, (the prior) has passed through the door and has fled to Avranches; I laugh at the adventure and tell you as a joke; but our judges of Avranches have taken it in a different spirit; it will have serious consequences, especially for Dom Hou&euml;l.&rdquo;]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="LMSM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LMSM"><cite title="source">Les l&eacute;gendes du Mont-Saint-Michel</cite></a> (1924) 182-3</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
